<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-19T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="730" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d730">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.001 Somoza, Anastasio/2:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-19T13:00:00-05:00">December 19, 1936—1
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>137. Your 240, December 14, 5 p.m.<note n="85" xml:id="d730fn85">Not
                                printed.</note> You should of course attend the inaugural
                            ceremonies. Keep the Department informed by telegraph if additional
                            special ambassadors are named.</p>
                        <p>Your 241, December 15, 10 a.m. It is not customary for the President to
                            send congratulatory telegrams to Presidents-elect either at time of
                            election or inauguration, and it is not believed that an exception
                            should be made in this case.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>